full_text: In this demonstration, we take a closer look at a commission plan. Then we'll modify a commission plan to include special rates for the personal auto line of business. Let's revisit the commission plan that we used in the previous demonstration. I clicked the link to CP03 on the Producer Summary screen. At the top of the screen are settings that apply to the commission plan as a whole. The Allowed Tiers area indicates this plan is available to all producer tiers, Gold, Silver, and Bronze. A commission plan can have more than one subplan. Here we see that CP03 has just one subplan, which is named Default. Default is the only required subplan. All primary producers using this plan will earn commission at the same rate and commission is always earned on billing. This is because there is only one subplan, Default. Currently, the Default subplan specifies a 10% rate for the primary producer regardless of the line of business. Succeed Insurance has a requirement for the rate for primary producers to be 15% for personal auto policies only. We can satisfy this requirement by adding another subplan. The first step for adding a conditional subplan is to put the commission plan into edit mode. I click Edit. Before I add a subplan, notice the default subplan has only 4 tabs. Next, I'll click Add. A fifth tab has appeared. All non-default subplans have a Subplan Availability tab for restricting usage of the subplan. Next, I'll name the subplan Personal Auto. Primary producers will earn commission at the rate of 15%. Secondary producers will earn commission at 10%. Producers with a role of referrer will earn commission at 5%. I click in the Earn Commissions field to specify when producers will earn commission according to this subplan. The list of values for Earned Commissions shows all possible payable criteria, including Custom, which would require configuration. I'll select On Billing. Suspend for delinquency is the last field on the General tab. I click Yes to suspend commission for delinquent policies. Now, I'll go to the Commissionable Items tab to specify which charge types will earn commission. Notice that no commissionable items are selected by default, so commissions will only be paid if something is listed here. For this subplan, commissions are paid on premium only. I'll click Add. I click in the Item field. Typically, commissions are paid on premium only. However, Billing Center can be configured to allow commissions to be paid on additional charge types. I select Premium from the list. Now we'll go to the Subplan Availability tab. This tab is available only for conditional subplans. The purpose of the Subplan Availability tab is to specify properties that restrict the usage of the subplan according to policy, producer, and account properties. Since the default subplan is always available with no restrictions, it has no need for an Availability tab. Each subplan has several options to restrict its usage. For example, we can limit a subplan to a specific product such as Personal Auto. This is what we want to do for this subplan. I click the Select button for Allow Products. This lets me select the individual products that this subplan applies to. By default, all products are allowed. I will click No for each one except Personal Auto. Notice I skipped Personal Auto because that is the product this conditional subplan will apply to. So now we have a conditional subplan that will be available only for Personal Auto. All other products will use the default subplan. The new subplan is complete. I click Update to save the changes to the Commission Plan. I click Return to Summary to go back to the Producer Summary screen. This concludes our demo on creating a Commission subplan. of the ! of the   of     Thank you.

Let's revisit the commission plan that we used in the previous demonstration. I clicked the link to CP03 on the Producer Summary screen.
At the top of the screen are settings that apply to the commission plan as a whole. The Allowed Tiers area indicates this plan is available to all producer tiers, Gold, Silver, and Bronze.
A commission plan can have more than one subplan. Here we see that CP03 has just one subplan, which is named Default. Default is the only required subplan.
All primary producers using this plan will earn commission at the same rate and commission is always earned on billing. This is because there is only one subplan, Default.
Currently, the Default subplan specifies a 10% rate for the primary producer regardless of the line of business.
Succeed Insurance has a requirement for the rate for primary producers to be 15% for personal auto policies only. We can satisfy this requirement by adding another subplan.
The first step for adding a conditional subplan is to put the commission plan into edit mode. I click Edit.
Before I add a subplan, notice the default subplan has only 4 tabs. Next, I'll click Add.
A fifth tab has appeared. All non-default subplans have a Subplan Availability tab for restricting usage of the subplan.
Next, I'll name the subplan Personal Auto.
Primary producers will earn commission at the rate of 15%. Secondary producers will earn commission at 10%.
Producers with a role of referrer will earn commission at 5%.
I click in the Earn Commissions field to specify when producers will earn commission according to this subplan.
The list of values for Earned Commissions shows all possible payable criteria, including Custom, which would require configuration.
I'll select On Billing.
Suspend for delinquency is the last field on the General tab. I click Yes to suspend commission for delinquent policies.
Now, I'll go to the Commissionable Items tab to specify which charge types will earn commission.
Notice that no commissionable items are selected by default, so commissions will only be paid if something is listed here.
For this subplan, commissions are paid on premium only. I'll click Add.
I click in the Item field.
Typically, commissions are paid on premium only.
However, Billing Center can be configured to allow commissions to be paid on additional charge types.
I select Premium from the list.
Now we'll go to the Subplan Availability tab.
This tab is available only for conditional subplans.
The purpose of the Subplan Availability tab is to specify properties that restrict the usage of the subplan according to policy, producer, and account properties.
Since the default subplan is always available with no restrictions, it has no need for an Availability tab.
Each subplan has several options to restrict its usage.
For example, we can limit a subplan to a specific product such as Personal Auto.
This is what we want to do for this subplan.
I click the Select button for Allow Products.
This lets me select the individual products that this subplan applies to.
By default, all products are allowed.
I will click No for each one except Personal Auto.
Notice I skipped Personal Auto because that is the product this conditional subplan will apply to.
So now we have a conditional subplan that will be available only for Personal Auto.
All other products will use the default subplan.
The new subplan is complete.
I click Update to save the changes to the Commission Plan.
I click Return to Summary to go back to the Producer Summary screen.
This concludes our demo on creating a Commission subplan.
